[thinking] I'll consider loading a class from an HTTP server, possibly using a local HttpServer available in the JDK. It looks like I should also prioritize using fetchClass in the Viewer subclass.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Exploring class loading methods**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m considering if I could avoid HTTP by subclassing and overriding fetchClass to return class bytes directly from a resource. However, the active findClass still executes and calls the overridden fetchClass. To define a class with Viewer, I need the bytes of a class that isn't already defined.
[thinking] 
[thinking] If I load a fixture from the resource with the same name in a custom loader, that might be okay, but I’m also worried about static fields and referencing assertj. Perhaps I could add a main method to validate arguments and throw an AssertionError in case of a mismatch. But then I wonder if I need to run the method twice.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Analyzing class loading behavior**
[thinking] 
[thinking] During the second run of the same class, findLoadedClass returns non-null, indicating that coverage is already considered reached even after the first call. I need to ensure findSystemClass is being used for Java classes from resolution.
[thinking] 
[thinking] When a custom loaded class requires java.lang.Object, the ClassLoader probably resolves it via loadClass("java.lang.Object") on the Viewer, which means findSystemClass will be hit. However, I'm uncertain if dynamic class definition is unsupported in Native Image. I need to look into that more.
[thinking] 
